ce:section.ce:para:
Cancer tissues are predominantly acidic and pH of many cancerous environments has been found to vary from 6 to 6.5, which is lower than the normal physiological pH [51]. This prompted us to load the hydrogel with an anticancer drug, that could be disembarked at acidic pH owing to the disruption of the i-motif structure of the DNA under acidic conditions. The chemotherapeutic drug Dox has been widely used for the treatment of broad range of cancers. As a proof of principle, Dox was encapsulated in the CD-DNA hybrid hydrogel by simple incubation in the solution phase. The encapsulation of Dox in the hydrogel takes place at both the CDs and DNA by two different mechanisms. While electrostatic interaction is the key to hold the positively charged Dox to the negatively charged CDs, intercalation of Dox takes place in the DNA [52]. The CD-DNA hydrogel was found to have high loading efficiency of ∼94% for Dox that was determined spectrophotometrically. The optical images of the hydrogel before and after drug encapsulation were taken in white and UV light that show orange color in daylight and pink fluorescence in the presence of UV light (Fig. 5
                        ). Thus, by simple visual inspection, the drug loading can be monitored in the hydrogel. Further, Dox loading in the hydrogel was monitored by change in the fluorescence intensity of CDs in the solution by steady state and time resolved fluorescence studies. The fluorescence intensity of CDs was decreased by ∼51% when 100 μg of Dox was added to CD-DNA solution (∼50 μg of CDs) (Fig. 6
                        B). The decrease in fluorescence intensity of CDs may be attributed to the static quenching of CDs on Dox encapsulation. The CD-DNA solution containing Dox shows emission at 590 nm (visible region) i.e. emission from Dox at excitation wavelength of 480 nm (Fig. 6C). The gradual decrease in the emission of CD at 430 nm with the simultaneous increase of the emission of Dox at 590 nm after sequential addition of the latter is well correlated and proves loading of the Dox in the hydrogel in solution state.
